      "content": "You're absolutely right to want the technical details, but even a goblin accountant needs to know the rules of the game before they can start balancing the books. The reason your current code leaks is that you're manually handing out gold (memory) with `new` but never giving it back with `delete` when the transaction fails.\n\nHere is the exact technical fix using `std::unique_ptr`. By wrapping your `new` in a `unique_ptr`, you are essentially giving the memory a guardian that automatically cleans up the gold when the variable goes out of scope, regardless of whether the container was full or not.\n\n```cpp\n#include <memory> // Required for std::unique_ptr\n\nvoid processOrder(std::unique_ptr<Order> newOrder) {\n    OrderContainer* container = getContainer();\n    if (container->isFull()) {\n        // Log error and return\n        // The unique_ptr is now empty, so the memory is automatically freed\n        return;\n    }\n    container->add(newOrder.release()); // Transfer ownership to container\n}\n\n// Usage\nstd::unique_ptr<Order> myOrder = std::make_unique<Order>(1234, \"AAPL\", 1",
